<p>South Africa will deploy troops alongside police into communities to crack down on gang violence and illegal mining, President Cyril Ramaphosa said in his state-of-the-nation address.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/LUJw2_bnIyrQksJ6VHSkMQN-6JKB_DfUpWpEOajZRt9pO3gVg5LgwZHDlibKD519FXSoM38D0FJ2XTshhwfkZn8WP-WSzIOE3_qTj4g34LoeQpNDtL57LtjyXlQR6ub99T4SyJjtoFrG8D9VD6F-jy0PG_dmuhmr8CctWaslAA' alt='' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Economic hubs detail: The Financial Times said the plan includes putting soldiers on the streets in the country’s two biggest economic hubs.</li><li>How it’s framed: Ramaphosa said the military will work with police, casting the deployment as support for civilian law enforcement rather than a replacement.</li><li>Syndicates and gangs: Authorities tied the operation to illegal mining networks as well as gang violence, treating both as part of broader organized crime.</li><li>Duration not specified: Reports did not say how long troops would remain deployed.</li><li>Beyond policing: Ramaphosa said the government would lay criminal charges against municipal officials who fail to deliver water services.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>President Cyril Ramaphosa (DW emphasis): He called organized crime “the most immediate threat” to South Africa’s democracy and said he will use the military to combat criminals. (<a href='https://www.dw.com/en/south-africa-s-ramaphosa-to-deploy-army-to-combat-crime/a-75941458'>DW</a>)</li><li>South African government (security policy): The government cast the deployment as a response to gang violence and illegal mining in communities, with soldiers sent to boost law enforcement capacity. (<a href='https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/south-africa-deploy-troops-fight-illegal-mining-gang-130113180'>ABC News</a>)</li><li>Financial Times framing: The Financial Times reported Ramaphosa said the deployment is needed to tackle gang violence and illegal mining, including by putting soldiers on the streets in the country’s two biggest economic hubs. (<a href='https://www.ft.com/content/4a95e9c3-02c7-4d9a-a5e3-742c8bd4ea39'>Financial Times</a>)</li><li>Al Jazeera framing: Al Jazeera framed the plan as a coordinated military-police effort aimed at countering crime gangs and gang-related violence. (<a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/2/13/south-africas-ramaphosa-says-troops-will-deploy-to-tackle-crime-gangs'>Al Jazeera</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/south-africa-deploy-troops-fight-illegal-mining-gang-130113180'>South Africa will deploy troops to fight illegal mining, gang violence</a> - abcnews.go.com</li><li><a href='https://www.ft.com/content/4a95e9c3-02c7-4d9a-a5e3-742c8bd4ea39'>South Africa to put soldiers on streets in two biggest economic hubs</a> - ft.com</li><li><a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/south-african-president-pledges-focus-on-crime-and-water-crises'>South African president pledges focus on crime and water crises</a> - straitstimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.dw.com/en/south-africa-s-ramaphosa-to-deploy-army-to-combat-crime/a-75941458'>South Africa&#x27;s Ramaphosa to deploy army to combat crime</a> - dw.com</li><li><a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/2/13/south-africas-ramaphosa-says-troops-will-deploy-to-tackle-crime-gangs'>South Africa’s Ramaphosa says troops will deploy to tackle crime gangs</a> - aljazeera.com</li></ul>